<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-565-932  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 565 932.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computerworld  August 28 1989 v23 n35 p4(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Exchanges push trader Audit plan. (Chicago commodity exchangesdeveloping computerized auditing system)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Booker, Ellis.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The Chicago Mercantile Exchange and the Chicago Board of Trade,the world's two largest commodity exchanges, have announced a $5million project to develop a computerized auditing system forfraud prevention.andP;  The Automated Date Input Terminal (AUDIT)system would use handheld order-entry terminals capable ofprocessing orders in real time and noting when each trade occurs.andO;Each exchange will provide $2.5 million toward research aimed atdeveloping keyboards for input and communications technology tolet traders transfer the data to centralized exchange computers.andO;The recent FBI fraud indictments of 46 traders gave the exchangesan incentive to accelerate automation efforts because the frantictrading-pit setting enabled conspirators to cheat customers withinside information.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     CommoditiesAutomationOrder EntryFraudAuditing.andO;Feature:   illustrationchart.andO;Caption:   On guard. (chart)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>